L 20. comitium] This was the most important spot in the Forum Romanum, the old meeting-place of the citizens of Rome. It was situated in the north-western end of it, under the Capitol, close to the Curia Hostilia which occupied its north-eastern side on a slightly higher level. The Comitium ‘was a regularly consecrated templum or space open to the air and not a covered building. The harangues delivered from the Rostra, which stood between the Comitium and Forum, were delivered to open-air assemblies of the people.' Burn Rome and the Gampayna p. 82, Nichols’ Roman Forum p. 143 ff„ p. 188 ff.
